"Just remember that
when you told me you loved me,

47:13.364 --> 47:15.264
"for one moment today,

47:15.266 --> 47:17.166
"I was truly happy.

47:18.869 --> 47:21.771
"It may be the last time
I ever am.

47:23.207 --> 47:24.273
"Love, Ryan.

47:24.275 --> 47:26.042
"P.S.

47:26.044 --> 47:28.945
Take good care of your heart."

47:28.947 --> 47:32.048
You know, when I filtered
for a maddie,

47:32.050 --> 47:33.049
I didn't get any hits,

47:33.051 --> 47:36.185
but maybe if I try a Ryan?

47:38.857 --> 47:41.257
I can't imagine what his life
must have been like.

47:41.259 --> 47:43.726
Ruined by one
single mistake.

47:43.728 --> 47:45.027
Not necessarily.

47:45.029 --> 47:46.629
If he was under 18,

47:46.631 --> 47:48.564
then his name would never
have been released.

47:48.566 --> 47:49.799
Nobody would ever know.

47:49.801 --> 47:52.034
Except for us.

47:52.036 --> 47:54.437
I'm not sure we should know.

47:55.739 --> 47:57.807
Let's just...

47:57.809 --> 48:00.810
Keep trying to find maddie.

48:00.812 --> 48:01.944
I think
we just did!

48:05.749 --> 48:08.784
It's not Madeleine,
it's Madison.

48:10.854 --> 48:12.722
There.

48:13.725 --> 48:15.458
I found him!

48:15.460 --> 48:16.759
It's a Ryan...

48:18.295 --> 48:19.295
Oh, wow.

48:19.297 --> 48:20.529
It's...

48:20.531 --> 48:21.998
Ryan hallett.

48:24.868 --> 48:26.869
Governor Ryan hallett.

48:28.171 --> 48:31.340
I suggest we adjourn
for the day,

48:31.342 --> 48:32.742
and resume this
discussion tomorrow.

48:32.744 --> 48:35.111
I'm sure you don't
want to be late to...

48:36.346 --> 48:38.180
Whatever.

48:39.816 --> 48:41.517
Oh, right.

48:41.519 --> 48:42.752
Mm... mm-hmm.

48:44.821 --> 48:46.055
Well, then.

48:46.057 --> 48:47.423
Good evening.

48:47.425 --> 48:49.191
Mm-hmm.

48:49.193 --> 48:51.427
I have my, um,
lecture this evening,

48:51.429 --> 48:52.762
and then Rita's
gonna call, so...

48:52.764 --> 48:54.497
Good night.

48:54.499 --> 48:56.365
Happy, um...

49:05.542 --> 49:07.109
Norman, I really think
you're making

49:07.111 --> 49:10.112
<i>too big a deal out of this.</i>

49:10.114 --> 49:12.515
My girlfriend says that
she doesn't have a boyfriend.

49:12.517 --> 49:13.683
I think that's a big deal.

49:13.685 --> 49:14.951
<i>But why would I want</i>

49:14.953 --> 49:17.253
the whole world
to know about us?

49:17.255 --> 49:19.121
Why wouldn't you?

49:19.123 --> 49:21.390
<i>Because the world is</i>
<i>a different place now, Norman.</i>

49:21.392 --> 49:24.193
I mean, everybody tells
everybody everything.

49:24.195 --> 49:26.062
I mean, they post it,

49:26.064 --> 49:27.163
<i>or they tweet it,</i>

49:27.165 --> 49:28.531
<i>and then it's just out there</i>
<i>forever, and...</i>

49:28.533 --> 49:30.333
Are you saying
that we're not forever?

49:30.335 --> 49:31.867
<i>No...</i>

49:31.869 --> 49:34.170
I'm saying,

49:34.172 --> 49:35.972
this is our life.

49:35.974 --> 49:38.207
We're not somebody's... hashtag.

49:40.178 --> 49:41.944
<i>Look, I'm really tired, Norman.</i>

49:41.946 --> 49:44.046
Can we talk about this
when I get back?

49:44.048 --> 49:45.247
<i>Sure.</i>

49:46.416 --> 49:48.084
I'll see you Monday.

49:48.086 --> 49:49.652
Until then, I guess
you're "free as a bird," huh?

49:49.654 --> 49:50.753
Norman...

49:50.755 --> 49:51.754
<i>Goodnight.</i>

50:36.099 --> 50:39.902
<i>"February 14, 1835.</i>

50:39.904 --> 50:41.003
<i>"My dearest...</i>

50:41.005 --> 50:42.438
<i>"I continue to gather strength</i>

50:42.440 --> 50:45.741
<i>"from the words we shared</i>
<i>when you visited me yesterday.</i>

50:45.743 --> 50:49.412
<i>"Though my body fails,</i>
<i>my spirit grows ever stronger,</i>

50:49.414 --> 50:51.614
<i>"and I am able to send you this.</i>

50:51.616 --> 50:54.016
<i>"They call it a Valentine,</i>
<i>my dear,</i>

50:54.018 --> 50:55.785
<i>"and they tell me</i>

50:55.787 --> 50:58.487
<i>it's all the rage in england</i>
<i>these days..."</i>

51:41.999 --> 51:48.871
♪ I know for certain
the one I love ♪

51:48.873 --> 51:50.139
♪ I'm through with flirtin' ♪

51:50.141 --> 51:54.110
♪ it's just you
I'm thinkin' of ♪

51:54.112 --> 51:56.579
♪ ain't misbehavin' ♪

51:56.581 --> 52:01.550
♪ I'm savin' my love for you ♪

52:30.213 --> 52:33.015
Norman?

52:34.217 --> 52:35.251
Norman!

52:37.420 --> 52:38.821
Were you here all night?

52:38.823 --> 52:39.822
Yes?

52:39.824 --> 52:40.890
No.

52:40.892 --> 52:41.991
Well...

52:41.993 --> 52:43.425
What's this?

52:43.427 --> 52:45.461
Oh, uh, that's
the antique card

52:45.463 --> 52:47.396
that serge gave me.

52:47.398 --> 52:48.397
It's beautiful.

52:48.399 --> 52:51.133
It's almost 200 years old.

52:51.135 --> 52:52.168
And all handmade?

52:52.170 --> 52:54.003
Yeah.

52:54.005 --> 52:55.437
Somebody sure did care
about somebody.

52:55.439 --> 52:57.173
Yeah.

52:59.277 --> 53:01.710
Good morning,
everyone.

53:01.712 --> 53:03.312
Norman.

53:04.814 --> 53:05.814
You are...

53:05.816 --> 53:06.849
Not yourself.

53:06.851 --> 53:09.318
I just need a shave.

53:09.320 --> 53:11.420
A gentleman
must never forsake

53:11.422 --> 53:13.255
his morning ablutions.

53:13.257 --> 53:14.657
Do what you must,

53:14.659 --> 53:16.292
and we'll regroup
at the grille

53:16.294 --> 53:18.194
at say, 10:00?

53:18.196 --> 53:19.228
Okay.

53:19.230 --> 53:20.262
Sorry.

53:28.638 --> 53:31.740
So, how was your evening?

53:31.742 --> 53:33.175
Lovely.

53:33.177 --> 53:35.211
Uh, spent it with a...

53:35.213 --> 53:36.212
A friend.

53:36.214 --> 53:37.346
And you?

53:37.348 --> 53:39.715
Oh, it was great.

53:39.717 --> 53:42.084
You know, uh,

53:42.086 --> 53:44.086
wine, candlelight, music.

53:45.755 --> 53:47.323
Ah.

53:47.325 --> 53:49.158
I, um, I did some research,

53:49.160 --> 53:50.526
and there is no record
of the governor

53:50.528 --> 53:51.660
being involved in
a hit-and-run,

53:51.662 --> 53:54.196
or ever having received a dui.

53:54.198 --> 53:56.165
However,

53:56.167 --> 53:58.934
there is a sealed record
for a Ryan t. Hallett

53:58.936 --> 54:00.169
that was filed 15 years ago

54:00.171 --> 54:01.604
with the clerk
of the juvenile court,

54:01.606 --> 54:02.605
which suggests

54:02.607 --> 54:04.073
that whatever he did back then

54:04.075 --> 54:05.074
was expunged,

54:05.076 --> 54:07.076
and that gives him
the legal right to say

54:07.078 --> 54:08.477
he doesn't have
a criminal record.

54:08.479 --> 54:09.478
My goodness.

54:09.480 --> 54:11.146
You did all this,

54:11.148 --> 54:13.949
and still had time
for a candlelight dinner?

54:14.918 --> 54:17.219
I got up early.

54:17.221 --> 54:18.454
Yes, well, impressive.

54:18.456 --> 54:20.789
But the issue is not

54:20.791 --> 54:22.791
governor hallett's
juvenile record.

54:22.793 --> 54:24.994
It is Madison alstrup's
delayed letter.

54:24.996 --> 54:28.530
Well, she was living
in Cheyenne, Wyoming,

54:28.532 --> 54:30.966
and working as a reporter
for the Cheyenne-union post,

54:30.968 --> 54:31.967
until about a year ago,

54:31.969 --> 54:33.002
when she packed up
her apartment,

54:33.004 --> 54:36.005
and left no forwarding address.

54:36.007 --> 54:37.640
I'm sure you'll think of
something, Ms. mcinerney.

54:37.642 --> 54:38.841
Um...

54:38.843 --> 54:40.643
I must attend to Norman.

54:40.645 --> 54:41.910
He seems a bit blue.

54:48.652 --> 54:50.586
Oliver!

54:51.855 --> 54:53.555
Hallett is
a good governor.

54:53.557 --> 54:55.591
Even his opponents
like him.

54:55.593 --> 54:57.126
Whatever he did,

54:57.128 --> 54:59.061
he turned himself in,

54:59.063 --> 55:00.929
and he paid his debt.

55:00.931 --> 55:03.632
If we deliver that letter
to a reporter,

55:03.634 --> 55:05.768
then we're
handing her the power

55:05.770 --> 55:07.503
to destroy a good man

55:07.505 --> 55:11.040
who was once just a stupid,
broken-hearted boy.

55:12.475 --> 55:15.077
What happens after we deliver
the letter to Ms. alstrup

55:15.079 --> 55:17.579
is between Ms. alstrup
and her conscience.

55:17.581 --> 55:19.415
Ah... ah-hah.

55:19.417 --> 55:20.416
Ah-hah?

55:20.418 --> 55:22.418
Well, this is about
your conscience.

55:22.420 --> 55:25.688
That lady cop that
you had a crush on,

55:25.690 --> 55:26.722
you haven't seen her
in 15 years,

55:26.724 --> 55:28.324
and it still bothers you

55:28.326 --> 55:29.558
that you allowed her
to get in the way

55:29.560 --> 55:31.827
of performing your duties
in a timely manner.

55:33.663 --> 55:34.630
Rita's right.

55:34.632 --> 55:36.265
I really am starting
to sound like you.

55:36.267 --> 55:39.001
Please keep me informed
of your progress.

55:39.003 --> 55:42.004
There must be something in here
we are missing.

55:43.606 --> 55:45.507
Oh, and the police officer.

55:45.509 --> 55:48.243
I never said I haven't
seen her since.

55:51.581 --> 55:55.918
I'm still unclear
how this got so out of hand.

55:55.920 --> 55:56.919
Somebody took
a selfie with us

55:56.921 --> 55:58.354
and tweeted it,

55:58.356 --> 55:59.355
and somebody else
posted it,

55:59.357 --> 56:00.422
and somebody
else pinned it,

56:00.424 --> 56:01.423
and before
you know it,

56:01.425 --> 56:04.360
Rita's gone viral
with her own hashtag.

56:04.362 --> 56:06.228
I have no idea
what you are talking about,

56:06.230 --> 56:09.231
but, uh, I am outraged.

56:09.233 --> 56:11.467
So was Rita,
I guess.

56:11.469 --> 56:12.601
But when you're in love,

56:12.603 --> 56:15.204
don't you want to just
shout it out to the world?

56:15.206 --> 56:16.438
Of course.

56:16.440 --> 56:17.439
For some reason,

56:17.441 --> 56:21.477
strangers have chosen
to shout it for you.

56:21.479 --> 56:23.278
You know what
her hashtag is?

56:23.280 --> 56:25.147
Norman, please.

56:25.149 --> 56:27.249
Let's, uh, not go there.

56:36.259 --> 56:38.627
Can I help you?

56:38.629 --> 56:40.396
Yes, I'm Shane mcinerney.
I called from...

56:40.398 --> 56:41.430
The post office.

56:41.432 --> 56:42.564
Right.

56:42.566 --> 56:43.532
I'm Becca.

56:43.534 --> 56:44.566
Hi.

56:44.568 --> 56:46.368
Hi.

56:47.804 --> 56:49.238
She never married.

56:49.240 --> 56:50.272
She worked in Cheyenne

56:50.274 --> 56:51.273
until last year

56:51.275 --> 56:52.274
when she got sick,

56:52.276 --> 56:54.309
and Becca convinced her
to come down to Denver

56:54.311 --> 56:55.377
to see a specialist,

56:55.379 --> 56:58.280
and she never left.

56:58.282 --> 57:00.516
Good work,
Ms. mcinerney.

57:00.518 --> 57:02.518
Oliver,
I did my job,

57:02.520 --> 57:04.119
but can we just
think this through

57:04.121 --> 57:05.354
before we deliver this?

57:05.356 --> 57:08.056
If Ms. alstrup is
as sick as it sounds,

57:08.058 --> 57:09.324
she is highly
unlikely

57:09.326 --> 57:11.360
to create
a political scandal.

57:11.362 --> 57:12.528
I agree,

57:12.530 --> 57:14.096
but what Ryan says
in that letter

57:14.098 --> 57:15.597
could still be
pretty shocking.

57:15.599 --> 57:18.000
It's the last thing
she needs.

57:18.002 --> 57:20.402
What good could come
of this, really?

57:20.404 --> 57:21.670
Well, I think...

57:21.672 --> 57:23.472
It's always good to know
that you were loved,

57:23.474 --> 57:26.108
isn't it?

57:29.312 --> 57:30.412
May I help you?

57:30.414 --> 57:31.613
Yes, please, my name
is Oliver O'Toole.

57:31.615 --> 57:33.415
My colleagues and I were
hoping for a moment

57:33.417 --> 57:35.050
with Ms. Madison alstrup.

57:35.052 --> 57:36.618
She's not taking visitors.

57:36.620 --> 57:39.455
Oh, we don't want
to disturb her.

57:39.457 --> 57:41.323
Good, 'cause you won't.

57:43.092 --> 57:44.560
We do need

57:44.562 --> 57:47.362
to deliver this to her
briefly in person.

57:47.364 --> 57:48.430
We don't all
have to go in,

57:48.432 --> 57:49.998
just one of us.

57:50.000 --> 57:52.634
How about none of you?

57:52.636 --> 57:53.635
But we're from

57:53.637 --> 57:54.636
the United States
post office

57:54.638 --> 57:55.637
on official business.

57:55.639 --> 57:56.972
Honey, you could be
the governor of Colorado

57:56.974 --> 57:58.106
on official business,

57:58.108 --> 57:59.575
and you still wouldn't
get by me.

58:07.250 --> 58:08.283
He's almost finished.

58:08.285 --> 58:10.085
Thank you.

58:10.087 --> 58:11.520
I bet you guys
were busy this week.

58:11.522 --> 58:13.388
All those
valentines, right?

58:13.390 --> 58:15.023
350,000.

58:15.025 --> 58:18.060
And not one of them
was for me.

58:18.062 --> 58:20.529
There you go.
I'll see you Tuesday.

58:20.531 --> 58:23.499
Ricky, you hang in there, okay?

58:23.501 --> 58:24.600
Governor,

58:24.602 --> 58:27.035
these are the folks
from the post office.

58:27.037 --> 58:28.370
Hi, I'm Ryan.

58:28.372 --> 58:29.538
Governor,
I'm Oliver O'Toole,

58:29.540 --> 58:31.073
this is
Ms. Shane mcinerney.

58:31.075 --> 58:32.107
Hi. Thank you
for fitting us in.

58:32.109 --> 58:33.375
Oh, of course.

58:33.377 --> 58:34.443
So, I understand

58:34.445 --> 58:36.044
you have some kind of
a special delivery

58:36.046 --> 58:37.179
for me?

58:37.181 --> 58:39.414
Actually, we were hoping
you might deliver it for us.

58:39.416 --> 58:41.550
It was damaged

58:41.552 --> 58:43.051
when the mailbox
you dropped it in

58:43.053 --> 58:44.920
exploded.

58:50.159 --> 58:51.894
That was 15 years ago.

58:51.896 --> 58:52.928
Yes,

58:52.930 --> 58:53.996
but once it's mailed,

58:53.998 --> 58:55.264
we are still required
to deliver it

58:55.266 --> 58:56.231
to the name on the envelope.

58:56.233 --> 58:58.800
Of course.

58:58.802 --> 59:00.002
Governor,
it was necessary

59:00.004 --> 59:02.137
for us to read the letter

59:02.139 --> 59:03.805
in order to process it.

59:06.309 --> 59:07.342
Can you give us some time?

59:20.390 --> 59:21.990
So you know...

59:21.992 --> 59:22.991
Yes.

59:24.460 --> 59:28.297
Nothing can explain
or excuse what I did.

59:28.299 --> 59:30.032
He was homeless.

59:30.034 --> 59:32.834
No friends,
no family.

59:32.836 --> 59:34.736
There was no one
to even miss him,

59:34.738 --> 59:38.273
or to apologize to.

59:38.275 --> 59:39.675
He was never
identified.

59:39.677 --> 59:40.776
A man,

59:40.778 --> 59:41.910
just as alive as any of us,

59:41.912 --> 59:43.111
trying to do the best he could,

59:43.113 --> 59:45.180
and in a one moment...

59:45.182 --> 59:46.748
He was gone.

59:48.217 --> 59:50.285
I was a minor,
so it never came out,

59:50.287 --> 59:53.722
but I never took another drink,

59:53.724 --> 59:55.891
and I decided to spend
the rest of my life

59:55.893 --> 59:57.359
trying to make up for
what I did,

59:57.361 --> 01:00:00.195
but you never
really can.

01:00:01.297 --> 01:00:03.765
I can understand that.

01:00:05.868 --> 01:00:08.904
I always suspected
that this was out there,

01:00:08.906 --> 01:00:10.606
and that maddie
might show up one day,

01:00:10.608 --> 01:00:12.207
blow the whistle on me.

01:00:13.610 --> 01:00:14.610
Now I know why
she never did.

01:00:15.979 --> 01:00:17.045
For all she knew,

01:00:17.047 --> 01:00:19.147
I was only guilty
of being a user and a liar.

01:00:21.250 --> 01:00:22.718
And for all I knew,

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:26.855
she'd read this and decided
that I wasn't worth the trouble.

01:00:27.857 --> 01:00:29.257
It's funny, you know,

01:00:29.259 --> 01:00:31.059
how two people
who care about each other

01:00:31.061 --> 01:00:32.594
so much

01:00:32.596 --> 01:00:34.896
can let all their insecurities
get in the way

01:00:34.898 --> 01:00:36.698
and completely get it wrong.

01:00:39.569 --> 01:00:41.503
I'll bet she hates me now.

01:00:42.772 --> 01:00:45.607
Uh, actually, governor,

01:00:45.609 --> 01:00:48.076
I believe
she needs you now.

01:00:57.820 --> 01:00:59.054
What have you got there?

01:01:01.057 --> 01:01:02.824
Oh, uh...

01:01:07.497 --> 01:01:09.831
It's kind of
a Valentine love letter.

01:01:09.833 --> 01:01:11.433
Well, of course,
it's a love letter.

01:01:11.435 --> 01:01:13.669
Look at those two
little people kissing.

01:01:13.671 --> 01:01:15.737
It was mailed in 1835.

01:01:15.739 --> 01:01:20.676
Just the fact that it exists
could rewrite American history.

01:01:20.678 --> 01:01:21.677
One day, you're spilling
your heart out

01:01:21.679 --> 01:01:22.678
to your one and only,

01:01:22.680 --> 01:01:23.679
and a couple of centuries later,

01:01:23.681 --> 01:01:24.713
the whole world is reading

01:01:24.715 --> 01:01:28.083
what was only meant
for the two of you.

01:01:28.085 --> 01:01:29.084
Yeah...

01:01:30.453 --> 01:01:32.421
What's happened to the world?

01:01:34.457 --> 01:01:36.725
You put that away before
something happens to it.

01:01:36.727 --> 01:01:37.693
Yes, ma'am.

01:01:44.567 --> 01:01:46.668
And you're still
not getting in there.

01:01:47.670 --> 01:01:49.004
Yes, ma'am.

01:01:50.807 --> 01:01:52.641
Sometimes,
Ms. mcinerney,

01:01:52.643 --> 01:01:55.510
you are a complete
mystery to me.

01:01:55.512 --> 01:01:56.945
Sometimes?

01:01:56.947 --> 01:01:57.946
Why would you
lie to someone

01:01:57.948 --> 01:02:00.348
about not receiving
any valentines?

01:02:00.350 --> 01:02:01.717
That wasn't a lie.

01:02:01.719 --> 01:02:02.984
Oh, please,
Ms. mcinerney,

01:02:02.986 --> 01:02:04.319
if for whatever reason

01:02:04.321 --> 01:02:05.554
you were too
uncomfortable

01:02:05.556 --> 01:02:07.422
to decline
the invitation

01:02:07.424 --> 01:02:09.291
in person,

01:02:09.293 --> 01:02:11.960
you might try leaving
your mother out

01:02:11.962 --> 01:02:14.796
of your rather sad
attempts to dissemble.

01:02:14.798 --> 01:02:17.933
Oliver, I have no idea
what you are talking about.

01:02:17.935 --> 01:02:21.470
I'm talking about
dinner last night.

01:02:21.472 --> 01:02:23.205
Okay.

01:02:23.207 --> 01:02:24.406
I lied.

01:02:24.408 --> 01:02:26.174
I didn't have a date.

01:02:26.176 --> 01:02:28.643
But I didn't lie about
getting any valentines.

01:02:28.645 --> 01:02:30.479
I didn't receive
a single one this year,

01:02:30.481 --> 01:02:32.681
not even from my mother,
by the way.

01:02:35.384 --> 01:02:37.319
And you're one to talk.

01:02:37.321 --> 01:02:39.588
You said you spent the evening
with a friend.

01:02:40.623 --> 01:02:42.257
Well, if one cannot be
one's own friend, then...

01:02:42.259 --> 01:02:44.159
Then...

01:02:44.161 --> 01:02:45.527
Wait, how did you know?

01:02:45.529 --> 01:02:47.596
And please don't
change the subject.

01:02:47.598 --> 01:02:49.865
Oh, for heaven's sakes,
what are we even talking about?

01:02:49.867 --> 01:02:51.533
We're...

01:03:06.516 --> 01:03:07.516
Governor hallett,

01:03:07.518 --> 01:03:09.084
this is our colleague,
Norman dorman.

01:03:09.086 --> 01:03:11.119
Dorman.

01:03:11.121 --> 01:03:12.254
And this is...

01:03:12.256 --> 01:03:14.222
May I help you... governor?

01:03:14.224 --> 01:03:17.526
I understand Madison alstrup
is a patient here?

01:03:17.528 --> 01:03:18.760
She is.

01:03:18.762 --> 01:03:22.063
But I can't give you
her medical information.

01:03:22.065 --> 01:03:23.532
You don't have to.

01:03:23.534 --> 01:03:24.599
I know.

01:03:27.069 --> 01:03:28.336
When we were teenagers,

01:03:28.338 --> 01:03:30.639
she told me that she had
a congenital heart defect.

01:03:33.209 --> 01:03:34.276
"P.S.

01:03:34.278 --> 01:03:35.510
Take good care of your heart."

01:03:40.583 --> 01:03:43.351
I understand
that she doesn't want visitors.

01:03:43.353 --> 01:03:46.121
Well, folks like this,

01:03:46.123 --> 01:03:47.689
getting ready to go,

01:03:47.691 --> 01:03:50.492
it's not that
they don't want visitors,

01:03:50.494 --> 01:03:52.661
it's they don't want
just any visitor.

01:03:52.663 --> 01:03:55.630
And governor,
you're not just any visitor.

01:03:59.168 --> 01:04:00.402
Sir?

01:04:07.376 --> 01:04:08.376
I want to tell her the truth,

01:04:08.378 --> 01:04:10.111
and I want to tell her
I'm sorry.

01:04:12.515 --> 01:04:16.184
I just don't know
how to tell her goodbye.

01:04:19.188 --> 01:04:22.257
Uh...

01:04:22.259 --> 01:04:23.291
Um...

01:04:25.361 --> 01:04:28.230
When Abraham Lincoln
was 26 years old,

01:04:28.232 --> 01:04:29.297
he went to visit a woman

01:04:29.299 --> 01:04:34.035
who may or may not
have been his fiancee.

01:04:34.037 --> 01:04:36.404
Nobody's ever been
able to prove it.

01:04:36.406 --> 01:04:38.006
We do know that

01:04:38.008 --> 01:04:39.407
that she was
dying of typhoid,

01:04:39.409 --> 01:04:41.142
so he had gone
to say goodbye to her.

01:04:41.144 --> 01:04:43.945
Nobody knows what they said
to each other that day,

01:04:43.947 --> 01:04:44.946
but after he left,

01:04:44.948 --> 01:04:45.981
he was never
the same again.

01:04:45.983 --> 01:04:47.449
- Norman...
- She told him...

01:04:47.451 --> 01:04:49.784
Well, I like to think

01:04:49.786 --> 01:04:54.155
that she told him
not to dwell in the past,

01:04:54.157 --> 01:04:57.058
or blame himself for
what he couldn't change.

01:04:59.495 --> 01:05:02.731
And no one could ever understand
the special bond that they had,

01:05:02.733 --> 01:05:06.034
and I think that
she told him

01:05:06.036 --> 01:05:07.969
that none of it would matter

01:05:07.971 --> 01:05:10.205
if he didn't carry on
after she was gone.

01:05:13.042 --> 01:05:14.142
And, I guess
we both know,

01:05:14.144 --> 01:05:17.679
that he did.

01:05:29.191 --> 01:05:30.191
That girl.

01:05:30.193 --> 01:05:32.861
I'm guessing
she died around...

01:05:32.863 --> 01:05:34.729
1835?

01:05:35.731 --> 01:05:36.731
Yes, ma'am.

01:06:32.655 --> 01:06:34.889
Where is he?

01:06:36.892 --> 01:06:38.927
Norman could get lost
in an elevator

01:06:38.929 --> 01:06:41.863
when Rita isn't around.

01:06:44.133 --> 01:06:45.133
Oliver...

01:06:45.135 --> 01:06:46.234
Hmm?

01:06:46.236 --> 01:06:51.373
You know, if it weren't
for you being, well, you,

01:06:51.375 --> 01:06:54.642
that letter might not have
been delivered in time.

01:06:54.644 --> 01:06:55.777
If it weren't for me,

01:06:55.779 --> 01:06:58.113
that letter would have
been delivered 15 years ago,

01:06:58.115 --> 01:07:00.181
exactly on time.

01:07:00.183 --> 01:07:01.716
But you always say

01:07:01.718 --> 01:07:03.985
that God moves
in mysterious ways, right?

01:07:05.888 --> 01:07:06.955
Oh, that reminds me,

01:07:06.957 --> 01:07:08.957
I almost forgot...

01:07:08.959 --> 01:07:10.992
I have choir practice
in half an hour.

01:07:10.994 --> 01:07:11.993
You and Norman
can take the car

01:07:11.995 --> 01:07:13.228
back to the dlo,

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:14.596
I'll walk.

01:07:14.598 --> 01:07:17.232
The church is just
down the street.

01:07:18.868 --> 01:07:19.868
Oliver!

01:07:20.936 --> 01:07:22.570
You know
I wasn't lying

01:07:22.572 --> 01:07:24.773
when I said I didn't get
any valentines,

01:07:24.775 --> 01:07:25.940
right?

01:07:29.245 --> 01:07:31.880
Have a good weekend,
Ms. mcinerney.

01:07:39.989 --> 01:07:41.456
How's Rita?

01:07:41.458 --> 01:07:42.524
I saw her on TV.

01:07:42.526 --> 01:07:45.660
She looked pretty happy.

01:07:45.662 --> 01:07:47.762
She loves you, Norman,

01:07:47.764 --> 01:07:50.532
and you love her.

01:07:50.534 --> 01:07:54.169
Look, we both missed out
on a nice dinner last night,

01:07:54.171 --> 01:07:57.605
so what do you say
we close up,

01:07:57.607 --> 01:07:59.908
and we go grab something?

01:07:59.910 --> 01:08:01.009
Oh, that sounds...

01:08:01.011 --> 01:08:03.945
Wait, you didn't go out
with Oliver yesterday?

01:08:03.947 --> 01:08:05.380
No.

01:08:05.382 --> 01:08:06.815
How come?

01:08:06.817 --> 01:08:08.750
He didn't invite me.

01:08:08.752 --> 01:08:09.751
Yes, he did.

01:08:09.753 --> 01:08:10.718
No. No, he didn't.

01:08:10.720 --> 01:08:14.722
What about the
Valentine he sent you?

01:08:14.724 --> 01:08:16.890
Am I losing my mind?

01:08:16.893 --> 01:08:19.894
I didn't get any valentines!

01:08:22.064 --> 01:08:24.631
Something's weird.

01:08:24.634 --> 01:08:25.867
Hazel!

01:08:27.303 --> 01:08:28.470
Hazel...

01:08:28.471 --> 01:08:30.337
Do you remember
delivering any valentines

01:08:30.340 --> 01:08:31.805
to my house this week?

01:08:31.808 --> 01:08:33.741
Besides the one
from your mother?

01:08:33.743 --> 01:08:35.944
And the other one from...

01:08:35.946 --> 01:08:37.011
Well, you know.

01:08:37.013 --> 01:08:38.880
No, I don't know.

01:08:38.881 --> 01:08:39.881
I never got them.

01:08:39.883 --> 01:08:40.948
Of course you did.

01:08:40.951 --> 01:08:42.951
I gave them to Rita,
and we put them in the...

01:08:42.953 --> 01:08:43.917
Uh-oh.

01:08:43.920 --> 01:08:45.420
Uh-oh?

01:08:45.421 --> 01:08:48.389
She was carrying a box and...

01:08:49.959 --> 01:08:51.024
The decorations!

01:08:51.027 --> 01:08:53.495
Rita promised
that she'd give them...

01:08:53.497 --> 01:08:54.496
Norman!

01:08:57.765 --> 01:08:58.765
Ha!

01:08:58.768 --> 01:08:59.968
You wake up in the morning,

01:08:59.970 --> 01:09:01.336
and you never really know
how your day is going to end.

01:09:01.337 --> 01:09:02.337
Focus, Norman.

01:09:02.339 --> 01:09:03.438
It's a plain
cardboard box

01:09:03.439 --> 01:09:05.874
with a bunch of valentines
decorations in it.

01:09:05.876 --> 01:09:07.809
What, like crepe paper
and hearts and stuff?

01:09:07.810 --> 01:09:08.810
I don't know,

01:09:08.812 --> 01:09:09.911
I never opened it.

01:09:09.912 --> 01:09:11.712
Rita said that
it was all pretty old

01:09:11.715 --> 01:09:13.481
and I just...

01:09:13.483 --> 01:09:14.515
Hey, hearts

01:09:14.518 --> 01:09:15.550
and crepe paper
and stuff!

01:09:15.551 --> 01:09:16.885
Yes! That's it!

01:09:34.470 --> 01:09:37.171
"Dear Ms. mcinerney,

01:09:37.174 --> 01:09:39.307
"I've been thinking
that Valentine's day

01:09:39.309 --> 01:09:41.676
"might present
the perfect opportunity

01:09:41.678 --> 01:09:43.478
"for our long-promised dinner.

01:09:43.479 --> 01:09:45.580
I have reservations at..."

01:09:45.582 --> 01:09:47.081
"Montaldo's...

01:09:48.216 --> 01:09:49.417
"...a lovely spot

01:09:49.419 --> 01:09:52.554
"where we might share
some stimulating conversation

01:09:52.555 --> 01:09:53.654
"and enjoy the music.

01:09:54.790 --> 01:09:58.393
"It has been a long time
since we danced.

01:09:59.795 --> 01:10:01.663
"Awaiting your response,

01:10:01.665 --> 01:10:05.366
sincerely, Oliver O'Toole."

01:10:08.605 --> 01:10:09.671
He thought that I...

01:10:09.673 --> 01:10:11.773
And I thought that he...

01:10:11.775 --> 01:10:13.007
And look,
it's handmade.

01:10:14.109 --> 01:10:16.344
Somebody really cares
about somebody.

01:10:17.313 --> 01:10:18.980
Oh, Norman, I...

01:10:20.416 --> 01:10:22.183
Go on.

01:10:50.579 --> 01:10:51.879
Why aren't you in...?

01:10:57.586 --> 01:10:58.886
"I missed you."

01:11:04.960 --> 01:11:06.494
"I couldn't wait
until Monday."

01:11:10.599 --> 01:11:13.134
"I took the first flight back."

01:11:16.472 --> 01:11:18.106
No, I'm sorry.

01:11:18.108 --> 01:11:20.475
I should have known you were
just protecting what we have.

01:11:20.477 --> 01:11:23.144
It's just...

01:11:23.146 --> 01:11:24.379
You were there

01:11:24.381 --> 01:11:27.215
with those important,
sophisticated postal executives,

01:11:27.217 --> 01:11:28.883
and I just felt...

01:11:31.353 --> 01:11:32.787
I just thought...

01:11:32.789 --> 01:11:34.088
I just thought I lost you.

01:11:39.228 --> 01:11:41.062
Norman...

01:11:41.064 --> 01:11:43.231
That's impossible.

01:11:43.233 --> 01:11:47.502
Wherever I go,
I will always carry you with me.

01:11:58.113 --> 01:12:00.181
I want you on my raft.

01:12:00.183 --> 01:12:03.685
Aw...

01:12:03.687 --> 01:12:07.355
Wait, what on earth
does that mean?

01:12:07.357 --> 01:12:10.091
I love you.

01:12:11.193 --> 01:12:13.728
I love you, too.

01:12:41.657 --> 01:12:43.224
Maddie.

01:12:45.060 --> 01:12:46.728
Hey.

01:12:46.730 --> 01:12:48.930
It's Ryan.

01:12:50.866 --> 01:12:52.266
Ryan?

01:12:57.639 --> 01:13:00.141
It's been so...

01:13:01.944 --> 01:13:04.245
I waited.

01:13:05.714 --> 01:13:07.915
What happened?

01:13:07.917 --> 01:13:10.818
It's a long story.

01:13:11.820 --> 01:13:15.056
No stories,
just the facts, right?

01:13:17.760 --> 01:13:20.695
Well, this story
you gotta hear.

01:14:05.674 --> 01:14:06.774
Very nice!

01:14:06.776 --> 01:14:08.609
Okay, we'll see you
on Sunday.

01:14:13.015 --> 01:14:14.315
You were so good today.

01:14:14.317 --> 01:14:16.017
Wow, that was
really fun.

01:14:16.019 --> 01:14:17.618
That was wonderful.
You were great.

01:14:17.620 --> 01:14:18.986
- Really?
- Yeah.

01:14:18.988 --> 01:14:19.987
Little nervous.

01:14:19.989 --> 01:14:21.456
I ran in late.
I almost didn't make it

01:14:21.458 --> 01:14:23.391
- I was in such a...
- Why? What happened?

01:14:23.393 --> 01:14:25.560
Ms. mcinerney?

01:14:25.562 --> 01:14:26.561
Oh, my goodness.

01:14:26.563 --> 01:14:28.896
What a surprise.

01:14:28.898 --> 01:14:30.565
This is Dale,
uh, Travers,

01:14:30.567 --> 01:14:32.700
Dale, this is
Shane mcinerney.

01:14:32.702 --> 01:14:34.869
We work together at
the dead letter office.

01:14:34.871 --> 01:14:36.971
Wow! It's nice
to meet you, Shane.

01:14:36.973 --> 01:14:39.740
I don't think I've met any
of Oliver's friends from work.

01:14:39.742 --> 01:14:43.344
Well, I don't usually
get to... church.

01:14:43.346 --> 01:14:44.545
You should come sometime.

01:14:45.849 --> 01:14:47.982
Have you ever heard
Oliver sing?

01:14:47.984 --> 01:14:48.983
Yes.

01:14:50.018 --> 01:14:51.018
No.

01:14:51.020 --> 01:14:52.053
Well, sort of.

01:14:53.789 --> 01:14:55.690
Not, um, here.

01:14:56.693 --> 01:14:57.758
Well, you're really
missing something.

01:14:59.294 --> 01:15:00.928
I've got to get to work.

01:15:00.930 --> 01:15:02.697
Late shift.

01:15:02.699 --> 01:15:04.031
It was so nice
to meet you.

01:15:04.033 --> 01:15:05.032
Goodnight.

01:15:05.034 --> 01:15:06.033
Bye.

01:15:10.539 --> 01:15:12.507
She's, uh... a soprano.

01:15:12.509 --> 01:15:14.542
Ah.

01:15:14.544 --> 01:15:16.043
So, what brings you here?

01:15:16.045 --> 01:15:17.645
Oh.

01:15:17.647 --> 01:15:18.880
Uh...

01:15:21.583 --> 01:15:25.453
I just found it.

01:15:25.455 --> 01:15:27.455
Hazel had given
my valentines to Rita,

01:15:27.457 --> 01:15:30.725
and Rita put them
in a box, and...

01:15:37.032 --> 01:15:40.635
Am I... too late for dinner?

01:15:46.475 --> 01:15:49.710
"Just remember that

01:15:49.712 --> 01:15:52.413
"when you told me
you loved me,

01:15:52.415 --> 01:15:53.614
"for one moment today,

01:15:53.616 --> 01:15:58.719
"I was truly happy.

01:15:58.721 --> 01:16:01.622
"It may be the last time
I ever am.

01:16:01.624 --> 01:16:03.591
"Love, Ryan.

01:16:03.593 --> 01:16:06.260
"P.S.

01:16:06.262 --> 01:16:10.264
Take good care
of your heart."

01:16:17.372 --> 01:16:19.340
So...

01:16:19.342 --> 01:16:21.542
You loved me.

01:16:23.545 --> 01:16:25.546
I loved you.

01:16:27.316 --> 01:16:28.449
I tried.

01:16:30.619 --> 01:16:33.621
I tried to take care
of my heart, but...

01:16:33.623 --> 01:16:36.691
I'm sorry that
I wasn't there to help.

01:16:38.126 --> 01:16:39.627
What happened to the man?

01:16:42.097 --> 01:16:45.199
When I got out of
juvenile hall,

01:16:45.201 --> 01:16:47.735
I tried to find out about him,

01:16:47.737 --> 01:16:49.103
but nobody knew anything

01:16:49.105 --> 01:16:51.472
except that his body was still
at the county morgue,

01:16:51.474 --> 01:16:52.673
waiting to be claimed.

01:16:52.675 --> 01:16:55.109
I watched,
and I waited, and...

01:16:55.111 --> 01:16:56.811
Nothing.

01:16:56.813 --> 01:16:57.878
So, two years later,

01:16:57.880 --> 01:17:00.481
they let me
claim his ashes,

01:17:00.483 --> 01:17:03.751
and one beautiful
Saturday afternoon,

01:17:03.753 --> 01:17:07.154
I took his ashes to our tree,

01:17:07.156 --> 01:17:08.689
and I asked for forgiveness,

01:17:08.691 --> 01:17:10.825
and I made
a promise to him

01:17:10.827 --> 01:17:11.826
that I'd never forget

01:17:11.828 --> 01:17:15.663
that I'd been given
another chance

01:17:15.665 --> 01:17:17.198
to change my life,

01:17:17.200 --> 01:17:20.434
and I'd taken away his chance
to do the same thing.

01:17:22.304 --> 01:17:24.905
He died on the 23rd
of the month,

01:17:24.907 --> 01:17:28.509
so every month,
on the 23rd,

01:17:28.511 --> 01:17:30.845
no matter what,

01:17:30.847 --> 01:17:33.714
I make sure to get back there,

01:17:33.716 --> 01:17:35.683
back to that tree,
and to him,

01:17:35.685 --> 01:17:37.451
and I...

01:17:37.453 --> 01:17:38.486
Say a prayer.

01:17:41.757 --> 01:17:44.358
I'm still trying to
forgive myself, maddie.

01:17:45.927 --> 01:17:49.630
But, you know, when I'm there,

01:17:49.632 --> 01:17:53.467
somehow, I...

01:17:53.469 --> 01:17:56.370
Somehow, I do feel forgiven.

01:18:01.243 --> 01:18:05.279
You made
that Valentine.

01:18:05.281 --> 01:18:08.382
All by myself.

01:18:08.384 --> 01:18:10.184
The heart
was a little...

01:18:10.186 --> 01:18:12.319
It's perfect.

01:18:13.855 --> 01:18:16.290
I haven't gotten
a homemade Valentine

01:18:16.292 --> 01:18:18.893
since Joe cook made me one
in the second grade.

01:18:20.495 --> 01:18:22.630
He ran up to me
on the playground,

01:18:22.632 --> 01:18:24.398
shoved it in my hand,

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:26.667
and punched me in the shoulder.

01:18:28.738 --> 01:18:32.540
Well, then this must have been
something of a letdown.

01:18:34.343 --> 01:18:36.243
No.

01:18:36.245 --> 01:18:37.978
Not at all.

01:18:39.648 --> 01:18:40.981
I just wish...

01:18:43.952 --> 01:18:46.620
Why didn't you just say

01:18:46.622 --> 01:18:49.457
"hey, Shane,
did you get my invitation?"

01:18:50.892 --> 01:18:55.696
Well, um, a gentlemen
never makes assumptions

01:18:55.698 --> 01:18:57.998
about a lady's affairs.

01:18:58.000 --> 01:19:00.301
But I didn't have any...

01:19:00.303 --> 01:19:01.469
Affair.

01:19:01.471 --> 01:19:03.237
I got a massage, a pizza,

01:19:03.239 --> 01:19:05.239
and I took
a very long jog

01:19:05.241 --> 01:19:06.474
that happened
to take me

01:19:06.476 --> 01:19:09.744
past a...

01:19:09.746 --> 01:19:12.480
Gentleman's window,

01:19:12.482 --> 01:19:15.483
as he sat by candlelight

01:19:15.485 --> 01:19:16.951
reading a book

01:19:16.953 --> 01:19:20.588
with music
and a glass of wine.

01:19:20.590 --> 01:19:22.389
Hmm.

01:19:22.391 --> 01:19:23.858
I know.

01:19:23.860 --> 01:19:28.395
I know it was
a childish thing to do.

01:19:29.564 --> 01:19:32.299
Or perhaps we're just finally
old enough to know

01:19:32.301 --> 01:19:33.667
that sometimes

01:19:33.669 --> 01:19:36.337
matters of the heart
can hurt more than...

01:19:37.606 --> 01:19:39.406
Than a punch in the shoulder.

01:19:41.643 --> 01:19:43.277
Precisely.

01:19:48.750 --> 01:19:51.652
I'm sorry, Oliver.

01:19:54.389 --> 01:19:57.358
I'm sorry, too.

01:19:57.360 --> 01:19:58.359
Shane.

01:20:09.906 --> 01:20:11.338
So, is this

01:20:11.340 --> 01:20:12.706
the stimulating
conversation

01:20:12.708 --> 01:20:14.441
that you were
hoping for?

01:20:14.443 --> 01:20:15.709
Of course, mm-hmm.

01:20:15.711 --> 01:20:19.380
What were those
four aspects of love

01:20:19.382 --> 01:20:21.382
as defined by the greeks?

01:20:21.384 --> 01:20:23.350
There's philos,

01:20:23.352 --> 01:20:25.519
or "brotherly love."

01:20:25.521 --> 01:20:26.754
Storge, of course,

01:20:26.756 --> 01:20:28.823
which is sort of family...

01:20:28.825 --> 01:20:30.991
Well, a postable kind of love,

01:20:30.993 --> 01:20:32.526
and then there's...

01:20:32.528 --> 01:20:34.595
Let's just cut to the chase.

01:20:34.597 --> 01:20:35.796
Which one can we dance to?

01:21:11.933 --> 01:21:14.902
So, about that soprano,

01:21:14.904 --> 01:21:16.370
Dale?

01:21:16.372 --> 01:21:17.638
Oh, yes...

01:21:17.640 --> 01:21:19.673
What about her?

01:21:21.576 --> 01:21:23.544
How long have
you known her?

01:21:23.546 --> 01:21:28.549
Uh... 15, maybe 16 years.

01:21:30.151 --> 01:21:31.585
Hmm.

01:21:31.587 --> 01:21:32.720
What does she do?

01:21:32.722 --> 01:21:33.888
Oh, she's, uh...

01:21:33.890 --> 01:21:36.490
She's a police officer.

01:21:53.541 --> 01:21:55.643
"The water is wide

01:21:55.645 --> 01:21:58.178
"I cannot cross o'er

01:21:58.180 --> 01:22:02.917
"and neither have I
the wings to fly

01:22:02.919 --> 01:22:04.051
"give us a boat

01:22:04.053 --> 01:22:07.554
"that can carry two

01:22:07.556 --> 01:22:09.957
"and both shall row

01:22:09.959 --> 01:22:12.960
to yonder side..."

01:22:18.467 --> 01:22:20.034
<i>"And so, my love,</i>

01:22:20.036 --> 01:22:23.537
<i>"may these words explain all</i>
<i>that has been in my heart</i>

01:22:23.539 --> 01:22:26.040
<i>"and bring to you, if not joy,</i>

01:22:26.042 --> 01:22:29.076
<i>then light</i>
<i>to your present darkness..."</i>

01:22:32.948 --> 01:22:36.016
<i>"And remember,</i>
<i>tears may come at night,</i>

01:22:36.018 --> 01:22:38.953
<i>"but there is always joy</i>
<i>in the morning,</i>

01:22:38.955 --> 01:22:41.488
<i>"and always the promise</i>
<i>of a new day</i>

01:22:41.490 --> 01:22:44.558
<i>"if we will but believe in it.</i>

01:22:44.560 --> 01:22:45.859
<i>"Think of me sometimes</i>

01:22:45.861 --> 01:22:49.063
<i>"as you venture out</i>
<i>from this safe little village,</i>

01:22:49.065 --> 01:22:52.066
<i>"putting on all the love</i>
<i>and all the heartbreaks</i>

01:22:52.068 --> 01:22:53.467
<i>"of our past</i>

01:22:53.469 --> 01:22:55.002
<i>"as gentle armor,</i>

01:22:55.004 --> 01:22:58.505
<i>"and stepping out with faith</i>
<i>into a troubled world</i>

01:22:58.507 --> 01:23:00.007
<i>"that needs you.</i>

01:23:01.743 --> 01:23:04.511
<i>"Guard your heart, dear Abe,</i>

01:23:04.513 --> 01:23:08.782
<i>"as I am and will always be,</i>

01:23:08.784 --> 01:23:10.651
<i>your Ann."</i>

